node.text:
Swipe to see Saturn Dance!

I captured my first Saturn shot of the season on Tuesday Morning. Saturn and Jupiter are rising earlier and earlier, and will soon be prominent in the western sky in the evening. 

Why is Saturn dancing? When placed alongside my images from previous years, you can see the angle of the planet has shifted. This is due to the planet’s 26° tilt relative to the ecliptic plane, which is the path Earth travels on. In the coming years, the planet will continue to appear to angle up, with the rings becoming perfectly edge-on in early 2025.

On this day 52 years ago, two humans first set foot on another world. 

This accomplishment was the pinnacle of human ingenuity and cooperation, showing what can be accomplished with the right resources if we work towards a common goal. 

This image is a first for me- it’s the first image I’ve created that was over a gigapixel (a billion pixels). This was done by creating a mosaic of the moon, stars, and clouds, and stitching them together to create a massive photo. This was nearly a year in the making. 

To see the full size image, come check out my patreon (linked in my highlights) and scroll through all my images in their highest resolution! 

I will be doing a very limited print release soon. Please sign up via the link in my bio if you haven’t already if you’re interested in owning my work!

node.text:
My favorite objects to shoot, and what got me interested in this hobby to begin with, are nebulas. 

These colorful regions of space are where stars begin and end their lives, and they form impossibly vast and complex structures as the physics of the cosmos sculpt them. 

I’ve been neglecting sharing deep space objects lately because my deep space imaging equipment is packed up for my upcoming move. So I reprocessed one I captured last year, applying a similar color palette I used for the rosette nebula to the data. This is a blend of true and false color, as this nebula is a vivid red due to the abundance of hydrogen.

node.text:
Are the colors in space real? Or fake?

To answer that question, i captured the rosette nebula and threw away all my color data and hand painted it.  So this image, yes, the colors are entirely fake. This is the first time I’ve ever done that to an image, so as you scroll through my photos, the colors have true scientific meaning, either by representing burning gasses or by their accurate colors as your eyes would perceive them if they were bright enough to be visible to the naked eye. 

This is actually a re-edit of a photo I captured last January in true color, as the rosette nebula is in Monoceros, a winter constellation. 

You may have noticed I haven’t been posting as often lately. I’m currently in the process of listing my house for sale to move to another state, and it’s quite a lot of work, so sadly I haven’t been able to focus on producing images as much as I’d like. I’ll hopefully be back in the swing of things soon. 

If you haven’t done so yet, make sure you sign up for my next print sale launch via the link in my bio. I’ll be offering prints more rarely and in limited supply. I’m hoping to launch my next sale soon but am still fixing a few things in my store to make things operate more smoothly.

node.text:
Swipe to see how fast it moves!

I woke up before dawn this morning to drive up to the mountains for a chance at another lunar transit. Thankfully the clouds cleared just in the nick of time, allowing me to capture this moment that lasted just a half second long. I wanted to share that video to really drive home how unbelievably fast this thing moves, and how little room for error there is when capturing these. It blows my mind that I can see the ISS in broad daylight! 

To download the full size image and read a tutorial on how to capture these yourself, come check out my patreon! It’s linked in my highlights.

Have a wonderful Independence Day my fellow Americans! 🇺🇸

11 of my favorite astrophotos in one 8k image!

It’s been a while since I’ve done one of these, but I felt like my computer could use an upgraded wallpaper. Sometimes these compilations help remind me what I’ve accomplished since I started this hobby, and how I’ve been able to chase my dreams of space exploration without ever leaving my home. Each image I put a little bit of myself into, so even though I’m shooting things captured by people all around the world, my images are definitively mine. 

I just shared this as an 8k desktop wallpaper with patrons, on top of the 56 desktop and mobile backgrounds I shared on Sunday. If you want them, check it out, it’s super cheap and a nice way to support me while giving your pc or phone a facelift. You can find that linked in my highlights.

The shot you’ve been waiting for- the ISS transiting a pair of sunspots. 

I went live earlier today to show you the behind the scenes of capturing a solar transit (if you missed it don’t worry, it’s still available on my igtv). 

These events last about a half second, and require a lot of preparation to capture properly. This was captured using two cameras and two telescopes to get the shot the way I wanted it. On my livestream I mentioned they recently installed some new equipment on the ISS- you can actually see it in my image! The panels on the right show a darker patch in the separation that shows where the new panels were installed. I’m surprised I was able to see them! 

The full size image is over 100 megapixels. As always, check out my patreon if you would like to see my work in full resolution. That’s linked in my highlights.

node.text:
A reflection nebula, an emission nebula, and a dark nebula walk into a bar...

Over 5,000 light years away and over 20 light years across, the Trifid Nebula is a gem in the heart of Sagittarius and an example of 3 types of nebula rolled into one. The red areas are emission or “star forming” regions of space, while the blue is cooled dust that reflects the light of nearby stars, scattering the light so it appears blue. Dark nebula lay like shadows across the features, creating bold dust lanes.

This image was captured over just a few short hours in the desert in Landers, Ca to escape the light pollution and meet others in this awesome Astro community. 

While I shared my first attempt at processing this a year ago, I was never satisfied with how it turned out. So I came back to my dataset with fresh eyes to try and get the most out of the image. This is really a testament to how important processing is in this hobby. I’ll post a comparison pic on my story you can check out if you’re curious how it used to look. 

The treasures in the core of the Milky Way are here for the summer, so I’ll be sharing more images of them soon!

node.text:
“Shadows on the Zodiac”

The other night I spent some time shooting a 50-panel mosaic of the moon, using over 100,000 images total to get the surface in painstaking details. Check out my recent IGTV to watch a portion of the acquisition process. 
I’m often asked about the atmospheric “glow” around the moon in my images, it is a product of the light scattering as it passes through Earth’s atmosphere and again as it passes through my optics. However, there is another source of “glow” out in space: the Zodiacal Light. 

The Zodiacal Light is thought to be caused by Mars, as powerful dust storms on the planet fling material into solar orbit. This composite image shows how objects would cast faint shadows in that dust if it were bright enough to see. 

I am still working through some kinks in my print store before launching my next sale, so if you would like this and other works in print, make sure you sign up for my newsletter (bottom of the website linked in my bio).

node.text:
A slowed down and looped version of the timelapse I just shared to my feed, showing how the sun produces “coronal rain” as streams of plasma ride the magnetic field back down to the surface. 

You can clearly see how the magnetic loop rises and falls in this video of the 4 hours it was captured.

Swipe to see how the sun looks through an iPhone versus after 4 terabytes of data compressed into a 7 second video. 

This was the featured I showed in my livestream yesterday, where I was slewing around the sun showing the prominences off of them. In real time they appear motionless, but when you capture them over a period of 4 hours they reveal a chaotic turbulent environment as moon-sized plasma gobs rain down through the solar atmosphere. The timelapse is the result of close to a million individual frames stacked and sequenced, played back at 1800x
